        <section id="welcome" class="section">
            <h2>Welcome, Dear Revert!</h2>
            <p>Assalamu Alaikum (Peace be upon you)! We extend our warmest welcome to you as you embark on this beautiful journey of discovering Islam. This page is dedicated to providing you with essential information, guidance, and resources to help you understand and practice your new faith.</p>
            <p>Embracing Islam is a profound and blessed decision. Take your time, learn at your own pace, and know that there is a vast and supportive community ready to assist you. May Allah (God) ease your path and grant you immense blessings in this life and the hereafter.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="pillars" class="section">
            <h2>The Five Pillars of Islam</h2>
            <p>The Five Pillars are the fundamental practices that form the foundation of Muslim life. Understanding and striving to fulfill them is crucial for every Muslim.</p>
            <div class="info-grid">
                <div class="info-card">
                    <h3>1. Shahadah (Declaration of Faith)</h3>
                    <p>The declaration that there is no god worthy of worship except Allah, and Muhammad is His messenger. This is the cornerstone of Islam.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="info-card">
                    <h3>2. Salah (Prayer)</h3>
                    <p>Performing five obligatory prayers facing the Kaaba in Mecca, at specific times of the day. It's a direct connection with Allah.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="info-card">
                    <h3>3. Zakat (Charity)</h3>
                    <p>Obligatory charity paid annually to the poor and needy by those who meet certain wealth thresholds. It purifies wealth and helps society.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="info-card">
                    <h3>4. Sawm (Fasting)</h3>
                    <p>Fasting during the month of Ramadan from dawn until sunset. It's a spiritual discipline that fosters self-control and empathy.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="info-card">
                    <h3>5. Hajj (Pilgrimage)</h3>
                    <p>The pilgrimage to Mecca, obligatory once in a lifetime for those who are physically and financially able. It symbolizes unity and devotion.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="beliefs" class="section">
            <h2>Core Beliefs of Islam (Aqidah)</h2>
            <p>Beyond practices, Islam encompasses a profound set of beliefs that shape a Muslim's worldview and connection with the Divine.</p>
            <div class="info-grid">
                <div class="info-card">
                    <h3>Belief in Allah (God)</h3>
                    <p>The One, incomparable God, the Creator and Sustainer of the universe. He is unique, without partners or equals.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="info-card">
                    <h3>Belief in Angels</h3>
                    <p>Belief in Allah's unseen creations who carry out His commands, like Jibreel (Gabriel).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="info-card">
                    <h3>Belief in Holy Books</h3>
                    <p>Belief in the divine scriptures revealed by Allah, including the Torah, Psalms, Gospel, and the final revelation, the Holy Quran.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="info-card">
                    <h3>Belief in Prophets and Messengers</h3>
                    <p>Belief in all prophets sent by Allah, from Adam to Noah, Abraham, Moses, Jesus, and finally, Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon them all).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="info-card">
                    <h3>Belief in the Day of Judgment</h3>
                    <p>Belief that there will be a Day when all humanity will be resurrected and judged by Allah based on their deeds.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="info-card">
                    <h3>Belief in Divine Decree (Qadar)</h3>
                    <p>Belief that Allah has knowledge of all things, and everything happens by His will, while humans still have free will to choose between right and wrong.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="practice" class="section">
            <h2>Daily Muslim Practice & Lifestyle</h2>
            <p>Islam is a way of life, guiding Muslims in all aspects, from personal conduct to social interactions.</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Prayer (Salah):</strong> Consistency in five daily prayers.</li>
                <li><strong>Dua (Supplication):</strong> Regularly asking Allah for guidance, help, and forgiveness.</li>
                <li><strong>Reading Quran:</strong> Engaging with the Holy Quran, understanding its meanings, and reciting it.</li>
                <li><strong>Remembrance of Allah (Dhikr):</strong> Keeping Allah in mind through various phrases like "SubhanAllah" (Glory be to Allah).</li>
                <li><strong>Good Character:</strong> Striving to embody the best of manners, honesty, kindness, and compassion.</li>
                <li><strong>Modesty:</strong> Adhering to principles of modesty in dress and conduct for both men and women.</li>
                <li><strong>Halal & Haram:</strong> Understanding permissible (halal) and impermissible (haram) actions and foods.</li>
                <li><strong>Community:</strong> Engaging with the Muslim community for support, learning, and mutual encouragement.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="resources" class="section">
            <h2>Useful Resources for Reverts</h2>
            <p>Here are some types of resources that can further aid your learning:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Local Mosques/Islamic Centers:</strong> Connect with your local mosque for classes, community events, and mentorship.</li>
                <li><strong>Online Islamic Platforms:</strong> Websites and apps offering Quran translations, hadith collections, and lectures.</li>
                <li><strong>Islamic Books:</strong> Introductory books on Islam, the Seerah (biography of the Prophet), and basic Fiqh (jurisprudence).</li>
                <li><strong>Trusted Scholars & Teachers:</strong> Seek knowledge from qualified and reputable Islamic scholars.</li>
                <li><strong>Revert Support Groups:</strong> Online or local groups specifically for Muslim reverts to share experiences and ask questions.</li>
            </ul>
            <p><em>Always verify information with authentic Islamic sources and knowledgeable scholars.</em></p>
        </section>

